130 agreement fulfilled and shall issue a tax credit certificate. In such case, the department

HB 2211 11
131 shall reduce the tax incentive award and the corresponding amount of tax incentives the
132 eligible housing project shall claim under subsections 2 and 3 of section 620.2028 by the
133 same percentage that the housing project's average dwelling unit cost exceeds the
134 applicable maximum amount under subdivision (3) of section 620.2024, and such tax
135 incentive reduction shall be reflected on the tax credit certificate. If the department
136 issues a certificate under this subparagraph, the department of revenue shall accept the
137 certificate notwithstanding that the housing project's average dwelling unit costs exceed
138 the maximum amount specified in subdivision (3) of section 620.2024; or
139 c. If the housing project costs cause the housing project's average dwelling unit
140 cost to exceed one hundred fifty percent of the applicable maximum amount authorized
141 under subdivision (3) of section 620.2024, the department shall determine the eligible
142 housing business to be in default under the agreement, shall revoke the tax incentive
143 award, and shall not issue a tax credit certificate. The housing business shall not be
144 allowed a refund of sales and use tax under subsection 2 of section 620.2028.
145 (6) The maximum aggregate amount of tax incentives that may be awarded and
146 issued under section 620.2028 to a housing business for a housing project shall not
147 exceed one million dollars.
148 (7) If a housing business qualifies for a higher amount of tax incentives under
149 section 620.2028 than is allowed by the limitation imposed under subdivision (4) of this
150 subsection, the department and the housing business may negotiate an apportionment of
151 the reduction in tax incentives between the sales tax refund provided in subsection 2 of
152 section 620.2028 and the workforce housing investment tax credits provided in
153 subsection 3 of section 620.2028, provided the total aggregate amount of tax incentives
154 after the apportioned reduction does not exceed the amount under subdivision (4) of this
155 subsection.
156 (8) The department shall issue tax incentives under the program on a first-come,
157 first-served basis until the maximum amount of tax incentives allocated under
158 subdivision (4) of subsection 5 of this section is reached. The department shall
159 maintain a list of housing projects registered prior to January 1, 2027, and of housing
160 projects awarded tax incentives on or after January 1, 2027, so that if the maximum
161 aggregate amount of tax incentives is reached in a given fiscal year, such registered
162 housing projects that were completed but for which tax incentives were not issued, and
163 such housing projects that were completed and are awarded tax incentives but for which
164 tax incentives have not been issued, shall be placed on a waitlist in the order the housing
165 projects were registered or awarded tax incentives and shall be given priority for
166 receiving tax incentives in succeeding fiscal years.

